1 (ii) serve the large load customer;
2 (2) protects residential retail electric customers from the financial risks
3 associated with large load customers through the use of:
4 (i) load ramp periods;
5 (ii) minimum billing demand for electric distribution and
6 transmission service that is a high percentage of a large load customer’s contract capacity;
7 (iii) long–term contractual commitments and exit fees;
8 (iv) guarantee or collateral requirements; and
9 (v) penalties and reimbursement requirements for the large load
10 customer if the large load customer delays or cancels a project after the electric company
11 has begun buildout to accommodate the large load customer; and
12 (3) sufficiently ensures that the allocation of costs to large load customers
13 under the schedule does not result in customers that are not large load customers
14 unreasonably subsidizing the costs of large load customers under the schedule.
