30 SUBTITLE 20E. ALTERNATIVE COMPLIANCE FEE AUCTIONS.
31 9–20E–01.
32 (A) IN THIS SUBTITLE THE FOLLOWING WORDS HAVE THE MEANINGS
33 INDICATED.

210 HOUSE BILL 1532
1 (B) “ADMINISTRATION” MEANS THE MARYLAND ENERGY
2 ADMINISTRATION.
3 (C) “ALTERNATIVE COMPLIANCE FEE” MEANS A FEE PAID IN ACCORDANCE
4 WITH § 7–705 OF THE PUBLIC UTILITIES ARTICLE TO THE MARYLAND STRATEGIC
5 ENERGY INVESTMENT FUND ESTABLISHED UNDER § 9–20B–05 OF THIS TITLE.
6 (D) “AUCTION” MEANS AN ALTERNATIVE COMPLIANCE FEE AUCTION.
7 (E) “CAPACITY TARGET” MEANS A CALCULATION OF THE AMOUNT OF
8 RENEWABLE ENERGY GENERATION NEEDED IN A GIVEN YEAR TO SATISFY THE
9 RENEWABLE ENERGY PORTFOLIO STANDARD UNDER § 7–703 OF THE PUBLIC
10 UTILITIES ARTICLE FOR A SPECIFIC YEAR, MINUS THE AMOUNT ALREADY
11 PROCURED FROM OTHER SOURCES.
12 (F) “COMMISSION” MEANS THE PUBLIC SERVICE COMMISSION.
13 (G) “RENEWABLE ENERGY” MEANS ENERGY GENERATED FROM:
14 (1) ONSHORE WIND ENERGY GENERATING SYSTEMS; OR
15 (2) UTILITY–SCALE SOLAR ENERGY GENERATING SYSTEMS, WHICH
16 MAY INCLUDE CO–LOCATED BATTERY STORAGE, THAT DO NOT PARTICIPATE IN NET
17 ENERGY METERING UNDER § 7–306, § 7–306.2, § 7–306.3, OR § 7–306.4 OF THE
18 PUBLIC UTILITIES ARTICLE.
19 9–20E–02.
20 (A) (1) FOR 2027 AND 2028, THE ADMINISTRATION SHALL CONDUCT, IN
21 CONSULTATION WITH THE COMMISSION, AN ANNUAL, COMPETITIVE, LOW–BID
22 ALTERNATIVE COMPLIANCE FEE AUCTION TO AWARD CONTRACTS TO ELIGIBLE
23 BIDDERS TO FUND PROJECTS FOR THE DEVELOPMENT OF RENEWABLE ENERGY
24 GENERATION IN THE STATE USING REVENUE FROM ALTERNATIVE COMPLIANCE
25 FEES.
26 (2) (I) THE ADMINISTRATION AND THE COMMISSION SHALL SET
27 THE CAPACITY TARGET FOR THE AMOUNT OF RENEWABLE ENERGY GENERATION
28 REQUIRED FOR 2027 AND 2028.
29 (II) IN DETERMINING THE CAPACITY TARGET FOR EACH
30 AUCTION, THE ADMINISTRATION AND THE COMMISSION SHALL USE A
31 TRANSPARENT METHODOLOGY, INCLUDING:

HOUSE BILL 1532 211
1 1. RENEWABLE ENERGY CREDIT SHORTFALLS FROM THE
2 PRIOR YEAR;
3 2. ANTICIPATED GROWTH IN RENEWABLE ENERGY OVER
4 TIME;
5 3. AVAILABLE ALTERNATIVE COMPLIANCE FEE
6 REVENUE;
7 4. MODELED EXPECTED ENERGY CLEARING PRICES;
8 AND
9 5. TRENDS IN IN–STATE RENEWABLE ENERGY
10 GENERATION.
11 (3) THE ADMINISTRATION AND THE COMMISSION MAY SET:
12 (I) A MINIMUM LEVEL OF MEGAWATTS REQUIRED FROM EACH
13 TYPE OF RENEWABLE ENERGY SOURCE IN THE AUCTION; OR
14 (II) SPECIFIC PROCUREMENT THRESHOLDS FOR ALL TYPES OF
15 RENEWABLE ENERGY SOURCES COLLECTIVELY.
16 (B) (1) THE ADMINISTRATION, IN CONSULTATION WITH THE
17 COMMISSION, SHALL DEVELOP AND CONDUCT THE AUCTIONS IN A MANNER THAT IS
18 COST–EFFECTIVE AND MAINTAINS AND PROMOTES THE DEVELOPMENT OF
19 RENEWABLE ENERGY IN THE STATE.
20 (2) THE COMPETITIVE AUCTION PROCESS MAY REQUIRE THE
21 ADMINISTRATION TO SOLICIT A SERIES OF BIDS FROM RENEWABLE ENERGY
22 PROJECT DEVELOPERS FOR THE DEVELOPMENT OF RENEWABLE ENERGY
23 GENERATION PROJECTS THAT ARE NEEDED TO MEET ELECTRICITY DEMAND IN A
24 COST–EFFECTIVE MANNER.
25 (C) (1) TO BE ELIGIBLE TO SUBMIT A BID UNDER THIS SECTION, A
26 PERSON MUST:
27 (I) BE A RENEWABLE ENERGY GENERATION PROJECT
28 DEVELOPER; AND
29 (II) MEET THE MINIMUM CREDIT AND OTHER ELIGIBILITY
30 REQUIREMENTS SET UNDER PARAGRAPH (2) OF THIS SUBSECTION.

212 HOUSE BILL 1532
1 (2) THE ADMINISTRATION, IN CONSULTATION WITH THE
2 COMMISSION, SHALL SET ELIGIBILITY REQUIREMENTS FOR BIDDERS, INCLUDING
3 REQUIRING EACH BIDDER TO:
4 (I) PROVIDE PROOF OF FINANCIAL INTEGRITY;
5 (II) POST A BOND OR OTHER SIMILAR INSTRUMENT;
6 (III) AGREE TO BE SUBJECT TO ALL APPLICABLE TAXES; AND
7 (IV) COMPLY WITH ANY OTHER REQUIREMENTS THE
8 ADMINISTRATION DETERMINES ARE IN THE PUBLIC INTEREST.
9 (D) (1) ELIGIBLE BIDDERS SHALL SUBMIT COMPETITIVE BIDS BY
10 SPECIFYING:
11 (I) THE ACTUAL AMOUNT OF MEGAWATTS TO BE GENERATED
12 BY THE RENEWABLE ENERGY GENERATION PROJECT; AND
13 (II) A PRICE PER MEGAWATT THAT WOULD BE REQUIRED FROM
14 THE AUCTION.
15 (2) THE ADMINISTRATION SHALL RANK BIDS FROM LOWEST TO
16 HIGHEST COST PER MEGAWATT AND AWARD FUNDS DERIVED FROM ALTERNATIVE
17 COMPLIANCE FEES TO THE LOWEST BID OR BIDS.
18 (3) THE ADMINISTRATION SHALL AWARD BIDS UNTIL THE CAPACITY
19 TARGET SET UNDER SUBSECTION (A)(2) OF THIS SECTION IS REACHED.
20 (4) THE BIDDER WHO SUBMITS THE LOWEST RESPONSIVE BID FOR
21 DEVELOPING A RENEWABLE ENERGY GENERATION PROJECT SHALL BE AWARDED
22 THE AMOUNT OF FUNDS TO BUILD THE RENEWABLE ENERGY GENERATION PROJECT.
23 (5) THE ADMINISTRATION MAY REFUSE TO ACCEPT SOME OR ALL OF
24 THE BIDS MADE IN A COMPETITIVE AUCTION IN ACCORDANCE WITH STANDARDS
25 ADOPTED BY THE ADMINISTRATION.
26 (6) (I) IF THE CAPACITY TARGET CAN BE MET AT A COST BELOW
27 THE ALLOCATED FUNDING, THE ADMINISTRATION MAY:
28 1. CARRY FORWARD ANY FUNDING TO THE NEXT
29 AUCTION, IF APPLICABLE; OR

HOUSE BILL 1532 213
1 2. APPLY THE FUNDS FOR ANY ADDITIONAL MEGAWATTS
2 OF RENEWABLE ENERGY GENERATION THAT HAVE BEEN OFFERED UNDER THE
3 AUCTION.
4 (II) ANY AMOUNT OF ALLOCATED FUNDING THAT IS NOT
5 CARRIED FORWARD OR APPLIED UNDER SUBPARAGRAPH (I) OF THIS PARAGRAPH
6 SHALL ACCRUE IN THE MARYLAND STRATEGIC ENERGY INVESTMENT FUND AND
7 MAY BE ALLOCATED FOR ANY PURPOSE FOR WHICH ALTERNATIVE COMPLIANCE FEE
8 REVENUE IS AUTHORIZED TO BE USED.
9 (E) (1) THE ADMINISTRATION SHALL SET DELIVERY DEADLINES FOR
10 EACH RENEWABLE ENERGY GENERATION PROJECT THAT IS AWARDED FUNDING
11 FROM AN AUCTION.
12 (2) THE DEADLINES SET IN PARAGRAPH (1) OF THIS SUBSECTION
13 SHALL INCLUDE MILESTONES THAT REQUIRE THE DEVELOPER TO MEET CERTAIN
14 DELIVERY GOALS DURING THE DEVELOPMENT OF A RENEWABLE ENERGY
15 GENERATION PROJECT.
16 (3) THE ADMINISTRATION MAY GRANT EXTENSIONS FOR DELIVERY
17 GOALS THAT ARE DELAYED DUE TO INTERCONNECTION OR PERMITTING
18 CHALLENGES OR DELAYS IF THE DEVELOPER PROVIDES DOCUMENTATION OF THE
19 CHALLENGE OR DELAY.
20 (4) THE ADMINISTRATION SHALL ESTABLISH A METHOD OF
21 COLLECTION AGAINST ANY DEVELOPER AWARDED A CONTRACT UNDER THIS
22 SECTION TO RECAPTURE ANY FUNDS RECEIVED AS A RESULT OF:
23 (I) MISAPPROPRIATION, OVERPAYMENT, OR FRAUD; OR
24 (II) FAILURE TO MEET MILESTONES OR DELIVERY DATES.
25 (F) WITHIN 90 DAYS AFTER ALL CONTRACTS FOR RENEWABLE ENERGY
26 GENERATION PROJECTS ARE EXECUTED, THE ADMINISTRATION SHALL PUBLICLY
27 DISCLOSE THE NAMES OF EACH SUCCESSFUL BIDDER AND THE MEGAWATTS TO BE
28 DELIVERED BY THE DEVELOPMENT OF THE RENEWABLE ENERGY GENERATION
29 PROJECT.
30 (G) ON OR BEFORE JULY 1, 2027, AND JULY 1, 2028, THE ADMINISTRATION
31 AND THE COMMISSION SHALL REPORT TO THE GENERAL ASSEMBLY, IN
32 ACCORDANCE WITH § 2–1257 OF THIS ARTICLE, ON THE ADMINISTRATION OF THE
33 IMMEDIATELY PRECEDING AUCTION, INCLUDING:

