24 ENERGY METERING PROGRAM THAT:
25 (1) INCREASES BENEFITS TO RATEPAYERS BY LOWERING ELECTRIC
26 SYSTEM COSTS THROUGH THE USE OF FLEXIBLE CUSTOMER–SITED RENEWABLE
27 ENERGY RESOURCES;
28 (2) PROVIDES FAIR COMPENSATION TO ELIGIBLE
29 CUSTOMER–GENERATORS;

HOUSE BILL 1532 221
1 (3) IS DESIGNED TO MAKE PROGRESS TOWARD MEETING THE STATE’S
2 DEMAND–SIDE, ENERGY STORAGE, AND CLEAN ENERGY GOALS; AND
3 (4) PROVIDES INCENTIVES FOR THE DEVELOPMENT OF DISTRIBUTED
4 GENERATION THAT ARE LESS THAN THE INCENTIVES PROVIDED BY THE NET ENERGY
5 METERING PROGRAM UNDER § 7–306 OF THIS SUBTITLE.
6 (C) THE COMMISSION, BY ORDER OR REGULATION, SHALL DEVELOP AND
7 IMPLEMENT, AS A SUCCESSOR PROGRAM TO THE NET ENERGY METERING PROGRAM
8 UNDER § 7–306 OF THIS SUBTITLE, A NET ENERGY METERING PROGRAM TO BEGIN
9 JULY 1, 2027, THAT:
10 (1) PROVIDES INCENTIVES FOR THE DEVELOPMENT OF DISTRIBUTED
11 GENERATION TO ELIGIBLE CUSTOMER–GENERATORS UNDER §§ 7–306 AND 7–306.3
12 OF THIS SUBTITLE AND COMMUNITY SOLAR ENERGY GENERATING SYSTEMS UNDER
13 § 7–306.2 OF THIS SUBTITLE;
14 (2) MINIMIZES RATEPAYER COSTS IN THE SHORT TERM AND IN THE
15 LONG TERM; AND
16 (3) BALANCES, ON A STATEWIDE BASIS AND ACROSS TECHNOLOGIES
17 AND INDUSTRY SECTORS PARTICIPATING IN NET ENERGY METERING:
18 (I) 1. FAIR COMPENSATION FOR ENERGY EXPORTS; AND
19 2. THE BENEFITS OF AN ELIGIBLE
