HOUSE BILL 1532 239
1 DERIVED FROM A NUCLEAR ENERGY GENERATING STATION APPROVED BY THE
2 COMMISSION UNDER § 7–1217 OF THIS SUBTITLE.
3 (b) The Commission shall adopt regulations that:
4 (1) establish the nuclear energy long–term pricing purchase obligation
5 sufficiently in advance to allow an electric company to reflect nuclear energy long–term
6 pricing costs as a nonbypassable surcharge that is added to the electric company’s base
7 distribution rate on customer bills;
8 (2) define rules that facilitate and ensure the secure and transparent
9 transfer of revenues and long–term pricing payments among parties;
10 (3) define the terms and procedures of the nuclear energy long–term
11 pricing schedule obligations, including:
12 (i) establishing a formula and process to adjust the value of the
13 long–term pricing schedule every 2 years based on projected wholesale market prices
14 adjusted by the locational value and earning potential in the PJM region of the nuclear
15 energy generating station; and
16 (ii) establishing a per megawatt hour cap on any long–term pricing
17 schedule specified in an order issued under § 7–1217 of this subtitle;
18 (4) require the Commission to establish an escrow account; and
19 (5) to meet the total statewide long–term pricing purchase obligation for
20 all applications approved in an order issued under § 7–1217 of this subtitle, require the
21 Commission to annually establish each electric company’s zero–emission credit purchase
22 obligation based on the most recent final electricity sales data as reported by PJM
23 Interconnection and measured at the customer’s meter in proportion to the electric
24 company’s share of statewide load.
25 (c) (1) Each electric company shall procure from the escrow account
26 established by regulation under this section a quantity of zero–emission credits equal to
27 the electric company’s respective percentage of retail electric sales each year.
28 (2) Subject to any escrow account reserve requirement the Commission
29 establishes, if there are insufficient zero–emission credits available to satisfy the electric
30 companies’ zero–emission credit purchase obligations, the overpayment shall be distributed
31 to electric companies to be refunded or credited to each distribution customer based on the
32 customer’s consumption of electricity supply that is subject to the renewable energy
33 portfolio standard.
34 (d) A debt, an obligation, or a liability of a nuclear energy generation project or of
35 an owner or operator of a nuclear energy generation project may not be considered a debt,
36 an obligation, or a liability of the State.

