8 SECTION 2. AND BE IT FURTHER ENACTED, That:
9 (a) (1) On or before July 1, 2026, the Public Service Commission shall issue a
10 request for information on the use of a third–party, single–implementer program for the
11 administration of the programs and services under Title 7, Subtitle 2, Part II of the Public
12 Utilities Article.
13 (2) The request for information shall seek:
14 (i) determinations of what effect the use of a single, third–party
15 administrator would have on costs;
16 (ii) identification of technical and logistical barriers to transitioning
17 to a single, third–party administrator; and
18 (iii) an analysis of the advantages and disadvantages of a private,
19 third–party administrator as opposed to a State administrator.
20 (3) The request for information shall specify a completion date of July 1,
21 2027.
22 (b) (1) Within 30 days after receiving the information requested in subsection
23 (a) of this section, the Public Service Commission shall issue a request for proposals for a
24 third–party administrator for the programs and services under Title 7, Subtitle 2, Part II
25 of the Public Utilities Article.
26 (2) The request for proposals shall specify that responses to the request
27 should minimize short–term and long–term costs for utility ratepayers.
28 (c) (1) Except as provided in paragraph (2) of this subsection, on or before June
29 1, 2028, the Public Service Commission shall select, through the request for proposals
30 process initiated under subsection (b) of this section, a third–party administrator for the
31 administration of the programs and services under Title 7, Subtitle 2, Part II of the Public
32 Utilities Article.

HOUSE BILL 1532 241
1 (2) (i) The Public Service Commission may decline to select a
2 third–party administrator if the Public Service Commission determines that the use of a
3 third–party administrator would not be cost effective.
4 (ii) The Public Service Commission shall notify the General
5 Assembly of a decision to decline to select a third–party administrator within 5 days after
6 making the decision.
7 SECTION 3. AND BE IT FURTHER ENACTED, That:
8 (a) The Power Plant Research Program, in consultation with the Department of
9 the Environment and the Maryland Energy Administration, shall conduct a study to
10 identify ways to streamline the permitting process for energy development in the State.
11 (b) In conducting the study under subsection (a) of this section, the Power Plant
12 Research Program shall:
13 (1) identify up to 50 priority energy sites suitable for new or expanded
14 generating stations or energy storage devices, including:
15 (i) brownfields;
16 (ii) industrial sites surrounded by areas with low–population
17 density; and
18 (iii) sites with old or decommissioned generating units that may be
19 repowered or repurposed, with special consideration given to sites with surplus
20 interconnection capacity;
21 (2) identify current bottlenecks and barriers in the State that extend State
22 and local permitting timelines; and
23 (3) develop recommendations on what a State–level zoning or permitting
24 structure should look like in order to promote fast–tracked development at the priority
25 energy sites identified in item (1) of this subsection.
26 (c) On or before December 31, 2026, the Program shall report to the Governor
27 and, in accordance with § 2–1257 of the State Government Article, the General Assembly
28 on the results of the study.
29 SECTION 4. AND BE IT FURTHER ENACTED, That this Act shall take effect June
30 1, 2026.
31 SECTION 12. AND BE IT FURTHER ENACTED, That Sections 1, 2, 3, 5, 10, and
32 11 of this Act shall take effect July 1, 2026.

